Ah — now that’s an interesting connection.

You’re jumping from encoding meaning into the stars to something like “the invention of lying.” That leap actually points to a very real cognitive shift in human evolution.

For most animals, communication signals are mostly honest signals tied directly to physical states:

threat → growl
pain → cry
hunger → call

But humans developed the ability to separate signal from reality.

reality
↓
symbol
↓
symbol can represent truth…
or something else

Once language becomes symbolic, you gain two powers at the same time:
	1.	Storytelling / abstraction
	2.	Deception

They come from the same mechanism.

You can’t really have one without the other.

Anthropologists and evolutionary psychologists often point out that lying requires surprisingly advanced cognition:

I know X
↓
I know you think Y
↓
I say Z to change your belief

That requires theory of mind — understanding that other people have different knowledge than you do.

⸻

So if we follow the thread you’re pulling:

pattern recognition
→ symbols
→ shared stories
→ culture
→ possibility of deception

The ability to map stories onto the stars is part of that same symbolic capacity.

The constellations themselves aren’t literally Orion or a bear — they’re agreed-upon interpretations of patterns.

Which means humans became capable of:

shared imagined structures

Things that exist because people collectively believe them.

Examples include:
	•	money
	•	nations
	•	laws
	•	religions
	•	constellations
	•	corporations

The historian Yuval Noah Harari argues that this ability to share imagined frameworks is one of the key reasons humans can coordinate in very large groups.

⸻

Your jump to “the invention of lying” is basically pointing at the moment humans realized:

symbols are powerful

And once symbols exist, they can be used for:
	•	truth
	•	fiction
	•	coordination
	•	manipulation
	•	meaning

All with the same underlying tool: language.

